From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000025 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Petr Parkan Janda <petronijus@bastla.com>
Date: Fri, 3 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] bus: ti-sysc: add child named clocks with clkdev_add() to
 beat MAX_DEV_ID

sysc_child_add_named_clock() aliases the module fck/opt clocks to the
child device with clkdev_create(), whose vclkdev_alloc() rejects device
names longer than MAX_DEV_ID (24 chars), poisons the alias with "bad"
and logs e.g.

  ocp:target-module@48210000:mpu:fck: device ID is greater than 24

for the mpu, pmu and iva target modules on every OMAP4 boot (their
composed child names are 26-30 chars). The same file already solves
this exact problem in sysc_add_named_clock_from_child() by allocating
a struct clk_lookup and calling clkdev_add() directly, "to avoid the
MAX_DEV_ID limit" -- do the same here. Besides silencing the error this
makes the alias actually usable by a child driver calling
clk_get(dev, "fck").

Signed-off-by: Petr Parkan Janda <petronijus@bastla.com>
---
--- a/drivers/bus/ti-sysc.c
+++ b/drivers/bus/ti-sysc.c
@@ -2376,9 +2376,25 @@
 	if (IS_ERR(clk))
 		return -ENODEV;
 
-	l = clkdev_create(clk, name, dev_name(child));
-	if (!l)
+	/*
+	 * Use clkdev_add() instead of clkdev_create() to avoid the MAX_DEV_ID
+	 * limit for clk_get(), exactly like sysc_add_named_clock_from_child()
+	 * above: ti-sysc child device names such as
+	 * "ocp:target-module@48210000:mpu" exceed 24 characters, so
+	 * vclkdev_alloc() logged "device ID is greater than 24" for the mpu,
+	 * pmu and iva target modules on every OMAP4 boot and poisoned the
+	 * alias with "bad".
+	 */
+	l = kzalloc(sizeof(*l), GFP_KERNEL);
+	if (!l) {
 		error = -ENOMEM;
+		goto put_clk;
+	}
+
+	l->con_id = name;
+	l->dev_id = dev_name(child);
+	l->clk = clk;
+	clkdev_add(l);
 put_clk:
 	clk_put(clk);
 
